{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Before installing, check if Git already exists. Open a terminal (Mac: Applications > Utilities > Terminal; Windows: press Win, type `cmd`, press Enter) and run `git --version`. If a version number appears, skip to the last step to verify. If you see an error, continue.",
      "title": "Check for an Existing Install"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open your web browser and go to `git-scm.com/downloads`. You'll see download options for Windows, macOS, and Linux. This is the official Git website, so it's the safest source.",
      "title": "Visit the Official Git Website"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click the download link for your operating system. On Windows, the installer (a `.exe` file) downloads automatically. On Mac, follow the Homebrew or installer instructions shown. On Linux, note the command for your distribution.",
      "title": "Download the Installer"
    },
    {
      "text": "On Windows, double-click the downloaded `.exe` file and click **Yes** if prompted for permission. The Git Setup wizard will open with a license agreement page. Click **Next** to continue. Mac and Linux users can skip to the next step.",
      "title": "Run the Windows Installer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click **Next** through the setup screens, keeping the default options — they work well for beginners. When you reach the final screen, click **Install**, wait for the progress bar to finish, then click **Finish**.",
      "title": "Accept the Default Settings"
    },
    {
      "text": "On Mac, open Terminal and run `brew install git` if you have Homebrew. If not, run `git --version` — macOS will offer to install the Xcode Command Line Tools, which include Git. Click **Install** in the dialog that appears.",
      "title": "Install on macOS"
    },
    {
      "text": "On Ubuntu or Debian, open a terminal and run `sudo apt install git`. On Fedora, run `sudo dnf install git`. Enter your password when prompted and press `Y` to confirm. Wait until the prompt returns.",
      "title": "Install on Linux"
    },
    {
      "text": "Close and reopen your terminal so it picks up the new installation. On Windows, you can also open the newly installed **Git Bash** from the Start menu — it's a terminal made specifically for Git.",
      "title": "Restart Your Terminal"
    },
    {
      "text": "In your terminal, type `git --version` and press Enter. You should see output like `git version 2.43.0`. If you see a version number, Git is installed and ready. If you get \"command not found,\" restart your computer and try again.",
      "title": "Verify the Installation"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Steer to a flat, stable spot away from traffic and stop the car. Avoid soft ground, hills, or curves. Turn on your hazard lights immediately so other drivers can see you.",
      "title": "Pull Over to a Safe, Flat Spot"
    },
    {
      "text": "Shift into Park (or first gear for a manual) and pull the parking brake firmly. The car must not be able to roll while you work. Turn off the engine.",
      "title": "Set the Parking Brake"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place wheel wedges or large rocks against the tires on the opposite end of the car. If the flat is in front, wedge the rear tires. This keeps the car from rolling once it's lifted.",
      "title": "Block the Opposite Wheels"
    },
    {
      "text": "Open your trunk and lift the floor panel to find the spare tire, jack, and lug wrench. Set them on the ground near the flat tire so everything is within reach.",
      "title": "Get the Jack and Lug Wrench"
    },
    {
      "text": "If your wheel has a plastic hubcap covering the lug nuts, pry it off using the flat end of the lug wrench. It should pop loose. Set it aside face-up so you can use it to hold the lug nuts later.",
      "title": "Remove the Hubcap (If Present)"
    },
    {
      "text": "With the car still on the ground, fit the lug wrench onto each lug nut and turn counterclockwise about a half turn. They may be tight — push down or use your body weight. Loosen only; do NOT remove them yet.",
      "title": "Loosen the Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Look under the car near the flat tire for the jack point — a reinforced metal notch or flat spot on the frame, usually marked in your owner's manual. Place the jack directly under it. Never jack under plastic trim or the floor pan.",
      "title": "Position the Jack Under the Frame"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the jack handle clockwise to lift the car slowly. Stop when the flat tire is about 6 inches off the ground. Check that the jack stays straight and stable. If it tilts, lower the car and reposition it.",
      "title": "Raise the Vehicle"
    },
    {
      "text": "Unscrew each lug nut fully by hand or with the wrench, turning counterclockwise. Place them in the upturned hubcap or your pocket so they don't roll away. You'll need all of them to mount the spare.",
      "title": "Remove the Lug Nuts"
    },
    {
      "text": "Grip the tire firmly at the 3 and 9 o'clock positions and pull it straight toward you off the wheel studs. It may be heavy — keep your back straight. If it's stuck, tap the back of the tire with your palm to break it loose.",
      "title": "Pull the Flat Tire Off"
    },
    {
      "text": "Lay the flat tire flat on its side under the edge of the car near the jack, if space allows. This acts as a safety cushion if the jack fails. You've now safely removed the flat and are ready to mount the spare.",
      "title": "Set the Tire Aside Safely"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Bring fresh water to a boil in a kettle, using about 350 ml (12 oz) per cup. Once boiling, remove it from heat and let it sit for 30 seconds. The ideal brewing temperature is around 200°F (93°C) — just off the boil.",
      "title": "Heat the Water"
    },
    {
      "text": "Weigh out 30 grams of coffee beans (about 4 tablespoons) for 500 ml of water. Grind them on a **coarse** setting — the grounds should look like breadcrumbs or coarse sea salt, not powder. Too fine a grind will slip through the filter.",
      "title": "Measure and Grind the Coffee"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour a splash of hot water into the empty French press, swirl it around, and dump it out. This warms the glass so your coffee stays hot during brewing. The carafe should feel warm to the touch.",
      "title": "Preheat the French Press"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour the coarse grounds into the bottom of the warmed carafe. Give it a gentle shake to level the bed of grounds so the water saturates them evenly.",
      "title": "Add the Grounds"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour the hot water over the grounds in a slow, circular motion until the carafe is filled to about 500 ml. Make sure all the grounds are wet. You should see a foamy layer — called the *bloom* — rise to the top.",
      "title": "Pour in the Water"
    },
    {
      "text": "After 1 minute, use a spoon to gently break the crust of grounds floating on top and give one slow stir. This ensures even extraction. Don't stir vigorously — just one or two gentle turns.",
      "title": "Stir the Bloom"
    },
    {
      "text": "Rest the lid on top of the carafe with the plunger pulled all the way up. Don't press yet. Set a timer for **4 minutes** and let the coffee steep undisturbed.",
      "title": "Place the Lid and Wait"
    },
    {
      "text": "When the timer goes off, press the plunger down slowly and steadily — it should take about 15–20 seconds. If you feel strong resistance, pull up slightly and try again. Stop when the filter reaches the bottom.",
      "title": "Plunge Slowly"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pour the coffee into your cup right away. Don't let it sit in the press — the grounds at the bottom will keep extracting and turn it bitter. If there's extra, transfer it to a separate carafe or thermos.",
      "title": "Pour Immediately"
    },
    {
      "text": "Take a sip and check the flavor. It should taste smooth and full-bodied. If it's bitter, use a coarser grind or shorter steep next time. If it's weak or sour, grind finer or steep 30 seconds longer. Enjoy your cup!",
      "title": "Taste and Adjust"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Grab a spade or garden fork, a rake, a wheelbarrow or bucket, compost, and gloves. If you have a soil pH test kit, bring it too — tomatoes grow best at a pH between 6.2 and 6.8.",
      "title": "Gather Your Tools and Materials"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pick a spot that gets at least **6–8 hours** of direct sun daily. Mark out a bed about 3–4 feet wide. Watch the area at midday to confirm no trees or structures cast shade on it.",
      "title": "Choose and Mark the Bed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pull out all weeds, grass, rocks, and old plant debris from the marked area. Grab weeds at the base and remove the roots — if roots stay behind, weeds will regrow. The bed should be bare soil when done.",
      "title": "Clear the Surface"
    },
    {
      "text": "Squeeze a handful of soil into a ball, then poke it. If it crumbles apart, it's ready to work. If it stays in a sticky ball, wait a day or two — working wet soil creates hard clumps that roots can't penetrate.",
      "title": "Check Soil Moisture"
    },
    {
      "text": "Push your spade or fork about **12 inches** deep, lift, and turn the soil over. Work across the whole bed, breaking up large clods with the tool's edge. Finished soil should look loose and crumbly, not compacted.",
      "title": "Loosen the Soil"
    },
    {
      "text": "Follow your test kit's instructions on a soil sample from 4–6 inches deep. If pH reads below 6.2, sprinkle garden lime as directed on the package. If above 6.8, add elemental sulfur. Skip this step if you don't have a kit.",
      "title": "Test and Adjust the pH"
    },
    {
      "text": "Spread a **2–3 inch** layer of compost or well-rotted manure evenly over the entire bed. Use your rake to distribute it — you should no longer see bare soil showing through the layer.",
      "title": "Spread Compost"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the compost into the top **6–8 inches** of soil with your fork, mixing until it's evenly blended. The soil should look uniformly dark with no thick pockets of pure compost remaining.",
      "title": "Mix In the Amendments"
    },
    {
      "text": "Scatter a balanced organic fertilizer (such as 5-5-5) over the bed at the rate listed on the package. Lightly rake it into the top inch or two of soil so it's incorporated, not sitting on the surface.",
      "title": "Add a Balanced Fertilizer"
    },
    {
      "text": "Rake the bed smooth and level, breaking up any remaining clumps. Then water gently until the top few inches are moist. Let the bed settle for **a few days to a week** before planting — the soil is now ready for tomatoes.",
      "title": "Level, Water, and Let It Settle"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Lay out your fabric, pattern pieces, fabric scissors, straight pins, measuring tape, and fabric marker on a large flat surface. Iron the fabric first if it's wrinkled — smooth fabric cuts more accurately.",
      "title": "Gather Your Materials"
    },
    {
      "text": "Fold the fabric in half with the **right sides** (the printed or brighter side) facing each other. Line up the edges so they match evenly. You should see the duller wrong side facing out on both sides.",
      "title": "Fold the Fabric Right Sides Together"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place the pillowcase pattern on the folded fabric. Align the edge marked *fold* exactly along the folded edge of the fabric. Check that the pattern's grainline arrow runs parallel to the fabric's selvage (the finished edge).",
      "title": "Position the Pattern"
    },
    {
      "text": "Use your measuring tape to check the distance from the grainline arrow to the selvage at both ends of the arrow. Both measurements should be equal. If not, shift the pattern slightly until they match.",
      "title": "Check the Grainline"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pin the pattern to both fabric layers, placing pins every 4–6 inches inside the cutting line. Point the pins toward the pattern's edges. Smooth the fabric as you go — it should lie flat with no ripples under the pattern.",
      "title": "Pin the Pattern in Place"
    },
    {
      "text": "Trace along the pattern's cutting line with a fabric marker or chalk. If your pattern doesn't include seam allowance, measure and mark a line ½ inch outside the pattern edge instead. You should see a continuous, visible line all the way around.",
      "title": "Mark the Cutting Line"
    },
    {
      "text": "Using sharp fabric scissors, cut along the marked line with long, smooth strokes. Keep the bottom blade resting on the table and move around the fabric rather than turning it. Do **not** cut along the folded edge.",
      "title": "Cut Along the Line"
    },
    {
      "text": "Before unpinning, snip small ¼-inch clips into the seam allowance at any notch marks (the small triangles) on the pattern. These marks help you match pieces later when sewing.",
      "title": "Transfer the Notches"
    },
    {
      "text": "Remove all pins and lift the pattern away. Unfold your fabric piece — you should have one symmetrical pillowcase panel. Measure it against the pattern's finished dimensions to confirm the size is correct. Repeat the steps for any remaining pieces.",
      "title": "Unpin and Check Your Pieces"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Grab your guitar and a tuner. A clip-on tuner or a free tuner app on your phone both work. Sit in a quiet spot so the tuner can hear each string clearly.",
      "title": "Get Your Tuner Ready"
    },
    {
      "text": "Clip the tuner onto the headstock, or open your tuner app and set it to chromatic or guitar mode. Standard tuning from thickest to thinnest string is **E A D G B E**.",
      "title": "Turn On the Tuner"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the thickest string (6th string) firmly with your thumb. Watch the tuner display — it will show the note it hears. You're aiming for a low **E**.",
      "title": "Pluck the Low E String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the tuning peg for the 6th string slowly while plucking. If the tuner shows a note below E or the needle is left of center, tighten the string. If it's above E, loosen it. Stop when the needle centers on E and turns green.",
      "title": "Tune the Low E to Pitch"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 5th string and tune it to **A** the same way. Make small peg adjustments and re-pluck after each turn. The tuner should settle exactly on A with the needle centered.",
      "title": "Tune the A String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 4th string and adjust the peg until the tuner reads **D**. If you overshoot and go sharp, loosen the string below pitch and tune back up — this helps the string hold its tuning.",
      "title": "Tune the D String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 3rd string and tune it to **G**. This string sits close to the others on the display, so double-check the tuner shows the letter *G*, not F# or G#, before centering the needle.",
      "title": "Tune the G String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the 2nd string and adjust until the tuner shows **B** with the needle centered. Pluck gently — thinner strings are easier to knock sharp with a hard pick attack.",
      "title": "Tune the B String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pluck the thinnest string (1st string) and tune it to a high **E**. Turn the peg in small increments — this string snaps most easily if you tighten it too far past pitch.",
      "title": "Tune the High E String"
    },
    {
      "text": "Go back and pluck each string from low E to high E, checking the tuner each time. Tuning one string can slightly shift the others. Touch up any string that's drifted off center.",
      "title": "Recheck All Six Strings"
    },
    {
      "text": "Strum an open E minor chord or all six open strings together. It should sound smooth and ringing, with no sour or wavering notes. If it sounds clean, your guitar is in standard tuning and ready to play.",
      "title": "Confirm With a Strum"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Turn the mode dial on top of your camera to **M** (Manual). This unlocks direct control of ISO, aperture, and shutter speed. The letter M should appear on your screen or viewfinder display.",
      "title": "Switch to Manual Mode"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press the **ISO** button and use the control dial to select a starting value. Choose ISO 100–200 for bright daylight or ISO 800–1600 for indoor or dim scenes. The number updates on your display as you turn the dial.",
      "title": "Set Your ISO"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the aperture dial to set your f-number. Use *f/2.8–f/4* for a blurry background, or *f/8–f/11* to keep more of the scene sharp. The f-number shown on your display changes as you turn the dial.",
      "title": "Choose Your Aperture"
    },
    {
      "text": "Turn the shutter speed dial to set your exposure time. Start with **1/125** for stationary subjects or **1/500** or faster for movement. The value appears on your display, such as `1/250`.",
      "title": "Set Your Shutter Speed"
    },
    {
      "text": "Half-press the shutter button and look at the exposure meter — a scale from **-3 to +3** in your viewfinder. Adjust shutter speed or ISO until the indicator sits at or near **0**. Negative means too dark, positive means too bright.",
      "title": "Check the Exposure Meter"
    },
    {
      "text": "Fully press the shutter button to capture a test image. Then press the **Playback** button (the triangle icon) to view it on the rear screen.",
      "title": "Take a Test Shot"
    },
    {
      "text": "While viewing your test shot, press **INFO** or **DISP** until the histogram appears. The graph should spread across the middle without piling up against the left edge (too dark) or right edge (too bright).",
      "title": "Review the Histogram"
    },
    {
      "text": "If the image is too dark, lower the shutter speed one step (e.g., `1/250` to `1/125`) or raise ISO. If too bright, do the opposite. Change only **one setting at a time** so you can see its effect.",
      "title": "Adjust for Brightness"
    },
    {
      "text": "Take another shot after each adjustment and recheck the histogram. Repeat until the meter reads near **0** and the histogram looks balanced. When highlights aren't blown out and shadows show detail, your exposure is set.",
      "title": "Confirm Proper Exposure"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Stand in front of a mirror or set your phone to record from the side. Wear flat shoes or go barefoot on a firm surface. You'll use the mirror or video to check your form at each stage.",
      "title": "Set Up Your Practice Space"
    },
    {
      "text": "Place your feet shoulder-width apart with your toes turned out slightly, about 15 to 30 degrees. Spread your weight evenly across your whole foot — heel, big toe, and pinky toe should all press into the floor.",
      "title": "Set Your Stance"
    },
    {
      "text": "Extend both arms straight out in front of you at shoulder height, or clasp your hands at your chest. This counterbalances your hips and helps you stay upright throughout the movement.",
      "title": "Position Your Arms"
    },
    {
      "text": "Take a deep breath into your belly and tighten your core as if bracing for a light punch. Keep your chest up and eyes looking straight ahead. Your spine should feel long and stable, not arched or rounded.",
      "title": "Brace Your Core"
    },
    {
      "text": "Push your hips back slightly, as if reaching for a chair behind you, then bend your knees. Both should happen together. Check the mirror: your knees should track over your toes, not cave inward.",
      "title": "Start the Descent with Your Hips"
    },
    {
      "text": "Continue lowering with control for about 2 to 3 seconds until your thighs are at least parallel to the floor. Keep your heels planted and chest lifted. If your heels lift or your back rounds, stop at that depth for now.",
      "title": "Lower to Parallel"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pause for one second at the bottom. Check the mirror or video: chest up, knees over toes, heels down, and weight balanced mid-foot. If anything is off, stand up and reset before the next rep.",
      "title": "Check Your Bottom Position"
    },
    {
      "text": "Press through your whole foot and squeeze your glutes to stand back up. Exhale as you rise. Your hips and shoulders should rise at the same rate — if your hips shoot up first, slow down and lead with your chest.",
      "title": "Drive Up to Standing"
    },
    {
      "text": "At the top, stand fully upright with your hips extended and glutes squeezed. Don't lean back. You're back at your starting stance, braced and ready for the next rep.",
      "title": "Finish Tall"
    },
    {
      "text": "Perform 3 sets of 8 to 10 slow squats, resting 60 seconds between sets. Review your video after each set and fix one flaw at a time — heels, knees, or chest. When all 10 reps look clean, you've mastered the form.",
      "title": "Practice a Full Set"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Separe **500 g de farinha de trigo**, 10 g de fermento biológico seco, 10 g de sal, 1 colher de sopa de açúcar e 300 ml de água morna. Deixe tudo à mão sobre a bancada limpa, junto com uma tigela grande e uma colher.",
      "title": "Reúna os ingredientes"
    },
    {
      "text": "Encoste o dedo na água: ela deve estar **morna, não quente** (cerca de 35 °C). Se queimar o dedo, espere esfriar. Água quente demais mata o fermento e a massa não cresce.",
      "title": "Teste a temperatura da água"
    },
    {
      "text": "Em uma tigela pequena, misture o fermento, o açúcar e 100 ml da água morna. Mexa bem com uma colher e deixe descansar por **10 minutos**.",
      "title": "Ative o fermento"
    },
    {
      "text": "Observe a mistura: ela deve estar com **espuma e bolhas** na superfície, com cheiro levemente azedo. Se não espumar, o fermento está vencido — descarte e recomece com fermento novo.",
      "title": "Verifique se o fermento espumou"
    },
    {
      "text": "Na tigela grande, coloque a farinha e o sal em lados opostos da tigela. Mantenha o sal longe do fermento no início, pois o contato direto reduz a força do fermento.",
      "title": "Misture a farinha e o sal"
    },
    {
      "text": "Faça um buraco no centro da farinha e despeje o fermento espumado e os 200 ml restantes de água morna. Misture com a colher até formar uma massa grossa e pegajosa, sem farinha seca no fundo.",
      "title": "Adicione os líquidos"
    },
    {
      "text": "Polvilhe um pouco de farinha na bancada limpa e transfira a massa da tigela para lá com as mãos. Ela vai grudar nos dedos no início — isso é normal.",
      "title": "Passe a massa para a bancada"
    },
    {
      "text": "Empurre a massa para frente com a base da mão, dobre-a sobre si mesma e gire um quarto de volta. Repita esse movimento de forma ritmada por **10 minutos**. Adicione farinha só se grudar muito.",
      "title": "Sove a massa"
    },
    {
      "text": "Estique um pedaço da massa entre os dedos: ela deve formar uma **membrana fina e translúcida** sem rasgar. Se rasgar fácil, sove por mais 2 a 3 minutos e teste de novo.",
      "title": "Faça o teste da membrana"
    },
    {
      "text": "Modele a massa em uma bola lisa, coloque em uma tigela untada com óleo e cubra com um pano úmido. Deixe descansar em local morno por **1 hora**, até dobrar de tamanho. A massa está pronta!",
      "title": "Deixe a massa descansar"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Junta un desarmador plano, uno de cruz, una llave inglesa, pinzas y trapos. Compra empaques y arandelas de repuesto en la ferretería. Si puedes, lleva una foto del grifo para conseguir las piezas correctas.",
      "title": "Reúne las herramientas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Busca las llaves de paso debajo del lavabo y gíralas en sentido horario hasta que cierren. Si no hay, cierra la llave general de la casa. Abre el grifo para verificar: solo debe salir un chorrito y luego nada.",
      "title": "Cierra el agua"
    },
    {
      "text": "Coloca un tapón o un trapo sobre el desagüe del lavabo. Esto evita que tornillos o piezas pequeñas caigan por la tubería mientras trabajas. Extiende una toalla para ordenar las piezas que vayas quitando.",
      "title": "Tapa el desagüe"
    },
    {
      "text": "Retira la tapa decorativa de la manija con un desarmador plano. Verás un tornillo debajo: aflójalo con el desarmador de cruz y jala la manija hacia arriba. Si está atascada, muévela suavemente de lado a lado.",
      "title": "Quita la manija del grifo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Con la llave inglesa, gira la tuerca de sujeción en sentido antihorario y retírala. Jala el cartucho o vástago hacia arriba con las pinzas. Anota su posición u toma una foto antes de sacarlo por completo.",
      "title": "Extrae el cartucho o vástago"
    },
    {
      "text": "Examina el empaque de goma en la base del vástago y las arandelas. Si están agrietados, aplanados o desgastados, ahí está la fuga. Compáralos con tus repuestos: deben tener exactamente el mismo tamaño y forma.",
      "title": "Revisa las piezas dañadas"
    },
    {
      "text": "Retira el empaque viejo con el desarmador plano e instala el nuevo en la misma posición. Si el cartucho completo está dañado, reemplázalo por uno idéntico. Aplica un poco de grasa de plomería a las piezas nuevas.",
      "title": "Reemplaza el empaque o cartucho"
    },
    {
      "text": "Inserta el cartucho o vástago en su posición original, guiándote por la foto que tomaste. Enrosca la tuerca de sujeción con la llave inglesa sin apretar de más. Coloca la manija, ajusta su tornillo y pon la tapa.",
      "title": "Arma el grifo de nuevo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Gira las llaves de paso en sentido antihorario para abrirlas lentamente. Abre el grifo poco a poco: al principio saldrá aire y agua a borbotones, es normal. Espera a que el flujo se estabilice.",
      "title": "Abre el agua otra vez"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cierra el grifo por completo y observa durante uno o dos minutos. No debe gotear. Revisa también debajo del lavabo con un trapo seco: si queda seco, la reparación fue exitosa. Si gotea, aprieta un poco más la tuerca.",
      "title": "Verifica que no gotee"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Look at the top of your screen and click the **File** menu in the upper-left corner of your document window. A menu with document options will open.",
      "title": "Open the File Menu"
    },
    {
      "text": "Click **Save** in the File menu. If this is a new document that has never been saved, a Save dialog box will appear asking where to store the file.",
      "title": "Click Save"
    },
    {
      "text": "In the Save dialog, click a folder where you want to keep your file, such as **Documents**. Pick a location you'll remember so you can find the file later.",
